    "source": "the_and_a_kale_of",
    "contenu": "The document appears to be a recipe for a dish using kale, along with a description of taste notes. Below I have structured the content from the document including the ingredient list, cooking instructions, and additional commentary.\n\n---\n\n### Serves: 4\n\n### Ingredients\n- 1 pound kale, chopped roughly into 1½-inch pieces\n- Kosher salt\n- 2 tablespoons grapeseed or other neutral vegetable oil\n- 1 tablespoon grated ginger\n- ½ red bell pepper, seeded and sliced\n- 3 tablespoons soy sauce\n- Freshly ground white pepper\n- Pinch of sugar\n\n### Instructions\n1. **Cook the Kale:**\n   - Cook kale in a large pot of boiling salted water, stirring occasionally, until the stems are almost cooked—they will still have a slight crunch—about 6–8 minutes. \n   - Drain the kale, shock it in cold water, then dry well (this is easiest in a salad spinner).\n\n2. **Sauté:**\n   - Heat the oil in a large skillet over medium-high heat. Add the ginger and peppers and cook until they begin to soften, about 2–3 minutes. \n   - Add the kale and cook until it is warm.\n   - Add the soy sauce, adjust the seasoning with salt, pepper, and sugar, and serve.\n\n### Our Taste Notes\n- The floral ginger and the sugar highlight the sweet side of the bell pepper.\n- The salty soy sauce pushes the fresh garden taste of the bell pepper and brings out the garden aspect of the kale. \n- Kale has a slight crunch, and its bitterness keeps the other tastes focused and distinct.\n- This dish would probably not be served alone, so it would be tasted only in the context of something rich and powerful like a glazed duck, where its bitterness goes to work punctuating another huge taste.\n\n### Additional Information\n- The document also has a section header for \"SAUSAGE WITH LAGER SAUCE AND APPLE BOUILLON,\" which might suggest following descriptions or recipes that were not included fully in the shown part of the document. \n\nThe structure above should help in understanding, following, or analyzing the document's recipe further."
