 distances and gorge on fermented fruits, leading to lethargic behavior.\n- **Monkeys**: Experience motor coordination loss and difficulties in climbing.\n- **Flying foxes**: Largest bats with human-like taste preferences, feed on mostly fermented fruits at night, which impacts their navigation due to the effects on their sonar from the rotten fruit.\n- **Bats**: Experience difficulties in navigation and movement due to the consumption of rotten fruit.\n\n**Citations**: \n- Robert Dudley's theories are referenced as a foundational explanation for the physiological adaptations observed in modern humans.\n- Ronald Siegel's research on animals' reaction to fermenting fruits provides empirical evidence supporting these theories.\n\n---\n\nThe document illuminates how evolutionary processes, through interactions with environmental elements like fruit fermentation, have shaped not just physical traits but also ingrained behavioral patterns observed across different species, including humans."
