    "contenu": "The document is a recipe titled \"Tuna with Rosemary and Citrus Tapenade\" and it serves 4 people. Below is the structured content of the recipe, which includes ingredients and instructions segmented into components for clarity:\n\n### Tuna with Rosemary and Citrus Tapenade\n\n**Servings:** 4\n\n#### Ingredients for Tapenade:\n- ¼ cup chopped Kalamata olives\n- ¼ cup chopped green picholine olives\n- 1½ tablespoons chopped fresh rosemary\n- 1 tablespoon grated orange zest\n- 2 teaspoons finely minced garlic\n- ½ teaspoon freshly ground black pepper\n- 1 tablespoon fresh lemon juice\n- 2 tablespoons orange juice\n- ½ cup extra virgin olive oil\n\n#### Ingredients for Tuna:\n- 4 6-ounce tuna fillets (each ¾ to 1 inch thick)\n- 1 tablespoon olive oil, or as needed\n- Salt and freshly ground black pepper\n\n#### Instructions:\n1. **Prepare the Tapenade:**\n   - In a medium bowl, whisk together Kalamata olives, green picholine olives, rosemary, orange zest, garlic, and pepper.\n   - Add lemon juice, orange juice, and ½ cup olive oil, and whisk to combine.\n   - The tapenade can be made up to 2 days ahead of time. Cover with plastic wrap and refrigerate. Bring to room temperature before cooking the tuna.\n\n2. **Cooking the Tuna:**\n   - Preheat the broiler or prepare a charcoal or gas grill.\n   - Brush each tuna fillet with 1 tablespoon of olive oil and season with salt and pepper.\n   - Cook the tuna fillets until browned on both sides, approximately 3 to 4 minutes per side.\n   - Transfer the tuna to dinner plates.\n\n3. **Final Preparation:**\n   - Rewhisk the tapenade mixture if separated.\n   - Spoon the tapenade over the cooked tuna fillets.\n\n#### Variation:\n- For greater pungency, the recipe suggests rubbing the fish with a paste made from finely minced garlic, rosemary, lemon juice, and olive oil, and then letting it refrigerate for 1 hour before cooking."
