    "source": "75a397eb-8bc4-4cf8-bbc8-d248d23925ea.pdf_page_158",
    "contenu": "### Tomato Information Document\n\n#### Introduction to Tomato Flavor\n- **Fresh Tomato Scent**: Raw tomatoes get their fresh, grassy, fatty scent from 2-isobutylthiazole and cis-3-hexenal. Once cooked, their flavor alters, becoming more sulphurous due to dimethyl sulphide, also found in cooked cabbage.\n- **Volatile Compounds**: Occur in tomatoes as they ripen on the vine or when disrupted, enhancing the enzymatic release of aroma molecules. Below 12°C (54°F), these processes slow down, impacting flavor retention during refrigeration.\n- **History and Types**: Tomatoes were first introduced in Europe in the 16th century. Various heirloom and standard types, ranging in color and size, are now available.\n\n#### Enhancing Tomato Flavor in Cooking\n- **Umami in Cooking**: To enhance flavor, one can add tomato stems, leaves, or skins to a dish. Scraping the bottom of a blanched tomato reveals a white fish layer rich in umami.\n- **Tomato Puree**: \n  - **Making**: Reduce fresh tomatoes to a thick sauce and store in a refrigerator.\n  - **Stock Base**: Use tomato puree in rich vegetable or fond brun for roasting or fresh recipes. It’s vital to dry out tomato pieces and add them early into dishes for enhanced flavor.\n- **Additional Tip**: Boost umami in brown sauces by sautéing chopped onions, garlic, and tomatoes, then completing with tomato seeds and skins.\n\n#### Culinary Tips\n- **Tomato Use**: Tomatine in tomatoes acts as a natural pest repellent but vanishes as tomatoes ripen, enhancing their traditional flavor.\n- **Shakshouka**: Mentioned as a flavorful Middle Eastern and North African dish utilizing tomato sauce with chili, pepper, and cumin.\n\n#### Related Aroma Profile: Tomato Puree\n- Cooking down tomatoes results in an aromatic shift from green-scented aldehydes to caramel notes and floral, rose-scented beta-damascone, along with onion and spicy clove notes.\n\n### Recommended Tomato puree pairings (Flavor Pairing Chart):\n| Ingredient       | Matches with Tomato Puree |\n|------------------|----------------------------|\n| Baked European sea bass | ○○●●●                      |\n| Baked king scallop      | ○○●○○                      |\n| Spanish chorizo         | ●●●○○                      |\n| Avocado                 | ●●○○○                      |\n| Lychee                  | ●●○○○                      |\n| Roast pork belly        | ●●●●○                      |\n| Usukuchi (light soy sauce) | ●●●○○                   |\n| Fenugreek leaf           | ●○○○○                     |\n| Raspberry                | ●●●○○                     |\n| Allspice                 | ●●●●○                     |\n\n- **Note**: In the chart, the number of filled circles (●) represent stronger flavor compatibility with tomato puree, while empty circles (○) indicate weaker compatibility.\n\n#### Page Information\n- Page Number: 158"
