    "contenu": "### The Quick Sip on Beaujolais\n\nWith its rush of vivid cherry, raspberry, and peach flavors, good Beaujolais is irresistible and as exuberant-tasting as childhood itself.\n\n#### Two Worlds of Beaujolais\n- **Old-style Beaujolais**: Made in a traditional manner.\n- **Contrived Beaujolais**: Very commercial type. The marketing phenomenon known as Beaujolais Nouveau belongs to this latter group.\n\n#### All About Beaujolais\n- **Grape Variety**: All Beaujolais is made from the Gamay grape, known for its deliciously deep, fruity flavor.\n- **Fermentation Technique**: Most Beaujolais wines utilize carbonic maceration, a special method that maximizes the wine's inherent fruitiness.\n\n#### Carbonic Maceration Process\n- **How it works**: Carbonic maceration isn't just about fermenting grape juice; it involves fermenting whole, uncrushed clusters of grapes, usually hand-picked and rot-free. This process enhances fruity aromas and flavors by fermenting the whole berries in an oxygen-free environment, allowing them to burst from internal carbon dioxide pressure, which also kick-starts fermentation.\n\n#### After Fermentation\n- **Aging**: Post fermentation, Beaujolais is usually stored in tanks for several months — some varieties briefly in new or relatively new oak barrels — before being sold. \n\nThis method, particularly effective with Gamay grapes, imbues the wine with vibrant and rich flavors, distinctive of the Beaujolais wine experience."
