    "contenu": "The document titled \"Marnie's Corner\" discusses the wine industry's contemporary debate regarding cork usage and their alternatives in bottling wine. Here's the structured extract of its content:\n\n---\n\n### MARNIE'S CORNER\n\nWithin the wine industry, there is much debate about corks and cork taint. Corks have served vintners well for centuries, shaping how wine is aged and stored. However, corks have a notable failure rate that many consider too high. Unfortunately, very few wine drinkers are aware of cork problems when they occur. This lack of detection can prevent the wine from impressing as much as it potentially could.\n\nThis inconsistency—from one bottle to the next—is damaging for vintners. It affects the business as not many can afford such variability that is characteristic of natural corks.\n\nIn response, many wineries have switched to alternative closures such as screw tops and synthetic corks. These technologies aim to enhance consistency and offer a better wine experience to the customer.\n\n---"
