    "source": "mcgee.pdf_page_438",
    "contenu": "The text discusses several types of flavorings derived from plants, focusing on annatto, cardamom, and cinnamon, detailing their characteristics, uses, and histories. Below is the structured summary based on the contents:\n\n### FLAVORINGS FROM PLANTS\n\n#### Annatto\n- **Description**: Annatto seeds are hard and difficult to grind finely. They are often heated in a liquid to extract their flavor and color, and then this mixture is strained out.\n- **Use**: Annatto pastes are commercially available and are mainly used for their aroma, which includes woody, dry terpene humulone (also found in hops).\n\n#### Cardamom\n- **Ranking**: Cardamom is the world’s third most expensive spice after saffron and vanilla.\n- **Origin**: Cardamom is indigenous to the mountains of southwest India and was exclusively grown there until about 1900.\n- **Production**: Guatemala is now the largest producer of cardamom.\n- **Characteristics**: Cardamom seeds develop from fibrous capsules that ripen at different times.\n- **Varieties**:\n  - **Malabar**: Small, round capsule with high content of delicate, flowery compounds.\n  - **Mysore**: Larger, three-angled capsule with mainly pine, woody, and eucalyptus notes.\n\n#### Cinnamon\n- **Description**: Cinnamon is the dried inner bark of trees in the tropical Asian genus *Cinnamomum*.\n- **History**: It is one of the first spices to reach the Mediterranean and was used in embalming by ancient Egyptians. It has been repeated in the Old Testament.\n- **Uses**: Today, cinnamon is predominantly used in sweet dishes and candies.\n- **Varieties**:\n  - **Ceylon or Sri Lankan cinnamon (C. verum or C. zeylanicum)**: Has a delicate, sweet aroma with a mild flavor.\n  - **Southeast Asian or Chinese cinnamon (often called cassia)**: Typically has a stronger flavor and aroma.\n\n### Points to Note\n- Large cardamom, such as **Amomum subulatum** (found in North India, Nepal, and Bhutan), is used in savory and rice dishes and in pickles.\n- **Gahwa**: An Arabic coffee made from cardamom and typically used in Arab countries where they consume 80% of their cardamom coffee.\n- Cardamom and cinnamon have interesting protective and astringent properties noted in their respective descriptions."
