    "source": "and_to_the_fish_a",
    "contenu": "The document is about different traditional methods of preserving fish, focusing mainly on smoking, salting, and drying. Here's a structured summary of the key information presented in the document:\n\n### Traditional Smoked Fish\n- **Origin & Types**: Includes salmon from Norway, Scotland, and Nova Scotia, herring from Germany, Holland, and Britain, as well as cod and haddock from Britain, and sturgeon from Russia.\n- **Flavor Enhancement**: Smoking imparts a flavor that masks stale fishiness and helps preserve the fish by imparting flavors and antibacterial properties.\n- **Process**: Traditionally, fish like Yarmouth herring remained ungutted, were saturated with salt, and then left to smoke for long periods, helping in preservation.\n- **Modern Advances**: Reduction in time from production to market by rail transport in the 19th century improved the efficiency of smoking fish. Contemporary methods use less salt, maintaining salinity at about 3% or under, limiting the smoking time to a few hours to weeks, and preserving modern smoked fish and shellfish often in cans.\n\n### Preliminary Salting and Drying\n- **Purpose**: Salt is applied to the fish before smoking for a few hours to days, sufficient to prevent microbial spoilage and to aid in drying the surface proteins of the muscle, enhancing flavor.\n- **Resulting Texture**: Creates a sticky layer of dissolved myosin which forms a shiny gel on the surface of the fish, adding to its aesthetic and taste.\n\n### Cold and Hot Smoking Techniques\n- **Cold Smoking**: \n  - Uses sawdust for smoke production.\n  - Fish remains relatively cool, below 85°F/30°C.\n  - Process densifies the fish without cooking, helping to preserve and enhance flavor without causing disintegration.\n- **Hot Smoking**: \n  - Produces more smoke at a cooler temperature than cold smoking but above 85°F/30°C.\n  - Hardens the surface, forms a barrier to moisture, and results in a denser fish consistency.\n\n### Lightly Salted, Strong-Smelling Fish: Surströmming\n- **Fermentation Process**: Involves less salt allowing bacteria to thrive and significantly influence flavor.\n- **Example**: Swedish Surströmming, where herring are fermented in barrels for 1-2 months then sealed in cans for up to a year.\n- **Flavor Components**: Prominent due to Halanaerobium, which produces hydrogen and carbon dioxide gases, hydrogen sulfide, and several acidic components, contributing to a strong smell akin to a mix of rotten eggs, rancid cheese, and vinegar. \n\nThrough these methods, various traditional and modern techniques help enhance the flavor and shelf-life of fish, adapting to changes in logistics and consumer preferences over time."
